               <div class="summary">
                  <p>As bioengineering continues to advance, new trends are shaping the future of healthcare, agriculture, and even space exploration. In this article, we explore the emerging technologies and their potential impact.</p>
               </div>

               <!-- Main Image -->
               <img src="Test_image.webp" alt="Bioengineering concept image" class="placeholder-image">

               <h2>Main Body</h2>
               <p>The field of bioengineering is at the cutting edge of technological innovation, and it promises to revolutionize a number of industries. From creating artificial organs to designing sustainable biofuels, bioengineers are driving change. In this article, we'll explore some of the key trends shaping the future of bioengineering.</p>

               <p>One of the most exciting areas is tissue engineering. This involves creating artificial organs and tissues that can replace damaged ones, potentially alleviating the shortage of donor organs. Scientists are even exploring the possibility of using 3D printing technology to "print" tissues with biological ink made of stem cells. <strong>Another key innovation is synthetic biology</strong>, where organisms are engineered to produce chemicals, medicines, or even materials like biodegradable plastics.</p>

               <!-- Smaller image inside the body -->
               <img src="Test_image.webp" alt="Smaller bioengineering-related image" class="smaller-image">

               <p>These innovations could also transform the field of agriculture. By engineering crops to be more resilient or nutritious, bioengineering could help address food security issues, especially in the context of climate change. In space exploration, bioengineers are investigating how to grow food in extraterrestrial environments, a necessary step for long-term missions to Mars or beyond.</p>

               <p>While there are many benefits, these technologies also raise important ethical questions. How will society manage the potential risks of creating genetically modified organisms, or the implications of growing human tissues in the lab? These are the challenges bioengineers and policymakers will need to navigate as we move into the future.</p>
            </section>
